163
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:37,440
are not exactly nine to five.
并不完全是朝九晚五。

164
00:07:37,440 --> 00:07:42,200
Okay, so this is a kind of a set phrase we use often in English because a lot of people
好的，这是我们在英语中常用的一种固定短语，因为很多人

165
00:07:42,200 --> 00:07:46,200
traditionally have worked from 9am to 5pm.
传统上都是从早上9点工作到下午5点。

166
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:48,160
They have a break at lunch, then they go home.
他们中午休息一下，然后回家。

167
00:07:48,160 --> 00:07:49,160
That's right.
没错。

168
00:07:49,160 --> 00:07:54,880
So this is a kind of measure for, this is a way to describe traditional working hours
所以这是一种衡量标准，一种描述传统工作时间

169
00:07:54,880 --> 00:07:56,300
or traditional jobs.
或传统工作的方式。

170
00:07:56,300 --> 00:07:58,880
So you can say, yeah, I have a really nice nine to five job.
所以你可以说，嗯，我有一份很不错的朝九晚五的工作。

171
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:02,040
You could say, I really don't want to work a nine to five job.
你也可以说，我真的不想做朝九晚五的工作。

172
00:08:02,040 --> 00:08:03,040
That's right.
没错。

173
00:08:03,040 --> 00:08:05,760
So you don't want a traditional job where you're working from nine to five.
所以你不想做那种从九点工作到五点的传统工作。

174
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:06,760
Right.
对。

175
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:10,280
Most people I think work a little bit longer than that, but this is just a way of saying
我想大多数人工作时间比那要长一点，但这只是一种说法，

176
00:08:10,280 --> 00:08:11,680
a traditional job.
指代传统工作。

177
00:08:11,680 --> 00:08:12,680
That's right.
没错。

178
00:08:12,680 --> 00:08:13,680
Okay.
好的。

179
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:14,680
Nine to five job.
朝九晚五的工作。

180
00:08:14,680 --> 00:08:20,240
Now, why don't we move on to Rebecca saying that she is used to working long hours or
现在，我们来看看Rebecca说她习惯了长时间工作

181
00:08:20,240 --> 00:08:21,440
being on call.
或随时待命。

182
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:22,440
Right.
对。

183
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:28,860
So this construction, to be used to, I'm used to doing this, is a way to say that I already
所以这个结构，“be used to”，我习惯做这个，是一种表达我已经

184
00:08:28,860 --> 00:08:29,860
do this.
在做这件事的方式。

185
00:08:29,860 --> 00:08:34,320
This is my experience or I have the habit of working unusual hours.
这是我的经验，或者我有在非正常时间工作的习惯。

186
00:08:34,320 --> 00:08:35,320
That's right.
没错。

187
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:41,040
So maybe for example, you live in a very noisy area in your neighborhood and somebody comes
所以比如，你住在一个很吵的社区，有人来

188
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:44,440
and visits you and they can't sleep because it's so noisy.
拜访你，他们因为太吵而睡不着。

189
00:08:44,440 --> 00:08:45,440
You are used to it.
你已经习惯了。

190
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:46,480
Oh, you say, Oh, I don't mind.
哦，你会说，哦，我不介意。

191
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:48,040
I'm used to the noise.
我习惯这噪音了。

192
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:51,120
But your friend who's visiting is not used to it.
但你的朋友来拜访却不习惯。

193
00:08:51,120 --> 00:08:52,120
Right.
对。

194
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:53,240
They don't have this noise at home.
他们家里没有这种噪音。

195
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:55,500
So that's what happens and it can't sleep.
所以就是这样，他们睡不着。

196
00:08:55,500 --> 00:08:59,560
So when you are used to something, you have the habit or you're accustomed to it.
所以当你习惯某件事时，你有这个习惯或者你适应了它。

197
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:00,560
That's right.
没错。

198
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:01,560
Okay.
好的。

199
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:02,560
And what about our last phrase?
那我们的最后一个短语呢？

200
00:09:02,560 --> 00:09:06,920
Our last phrase comes at the end and Rebecca is talking about the start date for this job.
最后一个短语出现在结尾，Rebecca在谈论这份工作的开始日期。

201
00:09:06,920 --> 00:09:10,120
She wants to know, when do you need to fill the vacancy?
她想问，你们需要什么时候填补这个空缺？

202
00:09:10,120 --> 00:09:11,120
Okay.
好的。

203
00:09:11,120 --> 00:09:12,120
To fill the vacancy.
填补空缺。

204
00:09:12,120 --> 00:09:16,400
Now, we have this word vacancy and that means that it's available, right?
现在，我们有“vacancy”这个词，意思是它是可用的，对吧？

205
00:09:16,400 --> 00:09:17,400
That's right.
没错。

206
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:19,640
So vacancy is an available thing.
所以“vacancy”是一个可用的东西。

207
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:23,080
It could be a vacant place.
可以是一个空位。

208
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:24,080
Like an apartment?
比如公寓？

209
00:09:24,080 --> 00:09:25,080
Like an apartment.
比如公寓。

210
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:27,320
In this case, a vacancy in a company.
在这种情况下，是公司里的一个空缺。

211
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:29,440
That means a job that is available.
意思是一个可用的职位。

212
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:30,440
That's right.
没错。

213
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:33,160
So she is asking when she can fill the vacancy.
所以她问什么时候可以填补这个空缺。

214
00:09:33,160 --> 00:09:36,640
So we use the verb fill, to fill a vacancy.
所以我们用动词“fill”，填补空缺。

215
00:09:36,640 --> 00:09:40,840
And this sounds a lot better than saying, Hey, when do I start working here?
这听起来比说“嘿，我什么时候开始在这里工作？”要好得多。

216
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:45,480
This is a polite way to say, when is the job going to begin?
这是一种礼貌的说法，问工作什么时候开始。

217
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:47,960
When do you need to fill the vacancy by?
你们需要什么时候填补这个空缺？

218
00:09:47,960 --> 00:09:51,400
I guess another way of saying it would be, when is the starting date?
我想另一种说法是，开始日期是什么时候？

219
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:52,400
Yes.
是的。

220
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:55,680
So as we say, also fill the vacancy is a very good option.
所以就像我们说的，“填补空缺”是一个很好的选择。

221
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:58,080
But don't say, when do I start working?
但不要说“我什么时候开始工作？”

222
00:09:58,080 --> 00:09:59,080
Or when do we start?
或者“我们什么时候开始？”

223
00:09:59,080 --> 00:10:01,120
Yeah, no, we can talk about that in a minute.
嗯，不，我们可以稍后讨论这个。

224
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:03,360
Let's listen first to our dialogue one more time.
我们先再听一遍对话。

225
00:10:03,360 --> 00:10:11,480
We'll be back shortly.
我们马上回来。

226
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:13,920
Could you tell me a little about the organization?
你能给我介绍一下这个组织吗？

227
00:10:13,920 --> 00:10:16,520
For example, how big is your office here?
比如，你们这里的办公室有多大？

228
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:22,880
Well, in total we have around 150 employees based in Hong Kong, with another 400 in our
嗯，我们在香港总共有大约150名员工，另外还有400名在

229
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:24,840
head office in Beijing.
北京的总部。

230
00:10:24,840 --> 00:10:28,920
The news desk staff in Hong Kong has around 80 staff.
香港的新闻编辑室大约有80名员工。

231
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:30,320
I see.
我明白了。

232
00:10:30,320 --> 00:10:32,400
And how about the working hours?
那工作时间呢？

233
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:38,300
Well, as you know, Rebecca, in journalism, work hours are not exactly nine to five.
嗯，Rebecca，你知道，在新闻行业，工作时间不完全是朝九晚五。

234
00:10:38,300 --> 00:10:40,460
You could be on call at any time.
你可能随时待命。

235
00:10:40,460 --> 00:10:43,760
But we do have to work very unsociable hours at times.
但有时我们确实需要在非常不规律的时间工作。

236
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:45,960
Well, I'm used to that, Mr. Parsons.
嗯，我习惯了，Parsons先生。

237
00:10:45,960 --> 00:10:47,760
So that's not really a shock for me.
所以这对我来说并不意外。

238
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:50,120
Good, as long as you understand that.
好，只要你明白这一点就行。

239
00:10:50,120 --> 00:10:53,200
And when do you need to fill the vacancy, Mr. Parsons?
那你们需要什么时候填补这个空缺呢，Parsons先生？

240
00:10:53,200 --> 00:10:58,180
Yesterday, but no, we are hoping to start from the beginning of next month.
昨天，但不开玩笑，我们希望从下个月初开始。

241
00:10:58,180 --> 00:10:59,680
That sounds ideal.
听起来很理想。

242
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:05,360
So talking about working hours, being on call or unsociable working hours, have you ever
所以说到工作时间，比如随时待命或者非正常工作时间，你有没有

243
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:09,360
had a job where you've had to work maybe through the night?
做过需要通宵工作的活儿？

244
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:13,120
Yes, I used to work in a movie theater when I was in college.
有啊，我上大学时在电影院工作过。

245
00:11:13,120 --> 00:11:15,200
I had a day job too, so it was kind of a mess.
我白天还有另一份工作，所以搞得一团糟。

246
00:11:15,200 --> 00:11:17,000
I was very unsociable.
我那时候很不合群。

247
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:21,720
But I worked at a movie theater and I would start working at 6 p.m. or 5 p.m. and I would
但我在电影院工作，通常下午5点或6点开始上班，

248
00:11:21,720 --> 00:11:23,960
work until 2 or 3 a.m.
一直干到凌晨两三点。

249
00:11:23,960 --> 00:11:26,960
And so it was always busiest on Friday and Saturday.
而且周五和周六总是最忙的。

250
00:11:26,960 --> 00:11:29,200
And so I could never go out with my friends.
所以我从来没法跟朋友出去玩。

251
00:11:29,200 --> 00:11:31,440
So while everyone was partying, you were at the movie theater.
所以当大家都在派对狂欢时，你却在电影院。

252
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:32,440
Exactly.
没错。

253
00:11:32,440 --> 00:11:36,360
Or they would come to the movies and I would sneak in and bring them popcorn.
或者他们会来看电影，我就偷偷溜进去给他们带爆米花。

254
00:11:36,360 --> 00:11:41,120
So these unusual working hours, it's very interesting because usually, although it is
这种不寻常的工作时间很有意思，因为通常虽然

255
00:11:41,120 --> 00:11:44,320
a little bit more of a sacrifice, they usually pay a little bit better, right?
要付出更多牺牲，但工资也会高一些，对吧？

256
00:11:44,320 --> 00:11:47,360
They do and there are some advantages.
确实如此，而且也有一些好处。

257
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:49,160
It means that you get to sleep in really late.
这意味着你可以睡到很晚。

258
00:11:49,160 --> 00:11:50,800
You don't have to wake up early.
不用早起。

259
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:53,320
And you have the day off, like the entire day to do something.
而且白天一整天都空闲，可以做点别的事。

260
00:11:53,320 --> 00:11:54,320
Exactly.
没错。

261
00:11:54,320 --> 00:11:55,320
What about you?
你呢？

262
00:11:55,320 --> 00:11:56,840
Have you ever worked unusual hours?
你有没有做过非正常时间的工作？

263
00:11:56,840 --> 00:11:58,160
Yes, yes.
有啊，有啊。

264
00:11:58,160 --> 00:12:03,760
I used to work for a newspaper and obviously people like their newspaper in the mornings.
我以前在一家报社工作，显然人们喜欢早上看报纸。

265
00:12:03,760 --> 00:12:05,240
So bright and early.
所以大清早的。

266
00:12:05,240 --> 00:12:06,240
Bright and early.
大清早的。

267
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:07,240
We're talking about 6 a.m.
我们说的是早上6点。

268
00:12:07,240 --> 00:12:12,040
So obviously, we would deliver the newspapers around 1 a.m., 2 a.m.
所以显然，我们会在凌晨1点、2点左右送报纸。

269
00:12:12,040 --> 00:12:14,440
From 1 a.m. to about 6 a.m.
从凌晨1点到大约早上6点。

270
00:12:14,440 --> 00:12:15,440
Wow.
哇。

271
00:12:15,440 --> 00:12:20,240
So yeah, pretty unusual and very difficult because, for example, some people, for them,
是啊，非常不寻常，也很辛苦，因为比如有些人觉得

272
00:12:20,240 --> 00:12:21,240
it's great to see the sunrise.
看日出很美好。

273
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:24,800
I've seen so many sunrises and it's not really romantic for me anymore.
我看过太多日出了，对我来说已经不再浪漫了。

274
00:12:24,800 --> 00:12:26,600
We would call you a night owl.
我们会叫你夜猫子。

275
00:12:26,600 --> 00:12:27,600
Yeah.
是啊。

276
00:12:27,600 --> 00:12:28,840
Someone who's more awake at night.
就是晚上更精神的人。

277
00:12:28,840 --> 00:12:30,320
That's right and I still am.
没错，我现在还是这样。

278
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:35,160
So we're really interested to know maybe if you had any unusual working hours.
所以我们很想知道，你有没有过什么不寻常的工作时间？

279
00:12:35,160 --> 00:12:36,720
Or do you work a 9 to 5?
还是你做的是一份朝九晚五的工作？

280
00:12:36,720 --> 00:12:39,320
Yeah, do you have a 9 to 5 job?
是啊，你有朝九晚五的工作吗？

281
00:12:39,320 --> 00:12:42,960
So come to our website EnglishPod.com, let us know and we'll see everyone there.
那就来我们的网站 EnglishPod.com 告诉我们吧，我们到时候见。

282
00:12:42,960 --> 00:12:43,960
Bye.
再见。

283
00:12:43,960 --> 00:13:12,320
Got it.
明白了。
